Germany, Year Zero
May 8 always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide, as I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry that I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies committed all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was directly transferred from his prison to the center of Berlin and tasked with setting up, from nothing, the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, and no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate issue, even though for our family, it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
What future?
"You must help," my mother said to me.
Therefore, I offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card labeled "victim of fascism," while others displayed an Iron Cross obtained for services rendered to the army at a later date.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It's practically unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the German "economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and mainly accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each side wanted to strengthen "its" part of Germany.
But there are nevertheless lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy unquestionably takes root more easily in a context of economic recovery.
For this, above all, it takes initiative from individuals who are eager to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, the father of Germany's "social market economy"), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Hence the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the former communist countries and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey with concern for the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
In a way, the country ignored its past to move forward into the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and political democracy, Germany confronted its past, with much success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatized countries therefore risk confusion.
Nevertheless, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
Ultimately, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8th, 2005 is an opportunity to look back on the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn toward the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
